Trimmed (not vendored — recover by re-fetching upstream):
  - BOOTAA64.EFI, BOOTIA32.EFI, BOOTLOONGARCH64.EFI, BOOTRISCV64.EFI
    (non-x86_64 EFI boot binaries; revisit when Phase 3 lands ARM64)
  - limine-tool-windows-x86/limine.exe (Windows host tool; we build
    the host tool from limine.c on Linux/macOS instead)
  - limine-bios-pxe.bin (PXE network boot; not used for ISO boot)

Kept even though they look optional:
  - limine-bios-hdd.h: required to compile the host `limine` tool
    from limine.c. Looks like an HDD-install thing, but limine.c
    #includes it unconditionally.

License:
  - LICENSE: BSD-2-Clause for the binaries (Mintsuki and contributors).
  - limine.h: 0BSD (zero-clause BSD), per its SPDX header.

To bump:
  1. Pick the new release: https://github.com/limine-bootloader/limine/releases
  2. curl -fLO  the new limine-binary.tar.xz; verify SHA-256 against
     the upstream .sig file.
  3. Extract; copy limine-bios.sys, limine-bios-cd.bin, limine-uefi-cd.bin,
     BOOTX64.EFI, LICENSE, limine.c, Makefile to vendor/limine/
     (overwriting the old versions). Drop everything else.
  4. curl the matching limine-X.Y.Z.tar.xz source release; extract
     limine-protocol/include/limine.h; copy to vendor/limine/limine.h.
  5. Update version, sha256, and size lines in this file.
  6. Re-run `make iso && tools/qemu-run.sh` to confirm the kernel
     still boots cleanly.
